#:proof{:extraction {:phases {}, :dependency-graph nil, :arse-questions nil, :classification :partial, :phase-count 0, :dep-graph-count 0, :arse-count 0}, :classification :proved, :reclassification-reason "Post-hoc: zero sorry with substantive declarations", :output "\n\n---\n\nTARGET SANITY CHECK — mentions-problem-objects? ✅ (plan/alignment explicitly reference the metric spaces \\(X,Y\\), the dense subset \\(A\\), and the uniformly continuous \\(f : A → Y\\)) · avoids-assuming-conclusion? ✅ (formal target only concludes existence/uniqueness of \\(F\\) after the hypotheses) · meaningful-without-prose? ✅ (the Lean statements exactly encode the extension theorem, so even without narration the artifacts describe a substantive result) · notes: helper lemma `dense_agree_implies_eq` records the density-based uniqueness argument used repeatedly in Stage 1.\n\n```clojure\n;; proof-plan.edn\n{:problem-id 'm99A04\n :frame-id 'apm-v2-m99A04-1775007855572\n :goal \"Extend a uniformly continuous map f : A → Y, where A is dense in the complete metric space X and Y is complete, to a unique continuous F : X → Y.\"\n :terms [{:name \"dense-approximation sequence\"\n          :meaning \"For every x ∈ X choose (a_n) ⊆ A with a_n → x.\"\n          :needed-because \"This lets us define the candidate extension by limits of points already in the domain.\"}\n         {:name \"uniformly-continuous ⇒ Cauchy control\"\n          :meaning \"Uniform continuity sends Cauchy sequences in A to Cauchy sequences in Y.\"\n          :needed-because \"Ensures the limit lim f(a_n) exists in Y (which is complete) and is independent of the approximating sequence.\"}\n         {:name \"unique extension via density\"\n          :meaning \"If two continuous maps on X agree on the dense subset A, they agree everywhere.\"\n          :needed-because \"Delivers uniqueness once the continuous extension has been defined.\"}]\n :strategy [{:id :s1\n             :formal-dependency \"metric completion lemmas for dense subsets and uniform continuity\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Stage 1 discussion: define F(x)=lim f(a_n) and check well-definedness + continuity\"\n             :why-this-now \"One construction handles existence, continuity, and uniqueness simultaneously, so structuring the Lean target around it avoids duplicated limit arguments.\"\n             :lean-target \"ApmCanaries.Frames.M99A04.Apm_v2_m99A04_1775007855572.extend_uniformContinuous_dense\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Mathlib already contains `UniformContinuous.extend` for dense embeddings; reuse that API if possible.\"}]\n :stage-status {:stage1 :done\n                :stage2 :done\n                :stage3 :in-progress\n                :stage4 :pending}}\n```\n\n```clojure\n;; formal-alignment.edn\n{:problem-id 'm99A04\n :main-claim {:informal-claim \"A uniformly continuous map f : A → Y, with A dense in the complete metric space X and Y complete, extends uniquely to a continuous map F : X → Y agreeing with f on A.\"\n              :formal-name \"extend_uniformContinuous_dense\"\n              :formal-target \"∀ {X Y : Type*} [MetricSpace X] [CompleteSpace X] [MetricSpace Y] [CompleteSpace Y]\\n   {A : Set X} (hA : Dense A) {f : A → Y},\\n   UniformContinuous f → ∃! F : X → Y, Continuous F ∧ ∀ ⦃x⦄ (hx : x ∈ A), F x = f ⟨x, hx⟩\"\n              :sanity-check {:mentions-problem-objects? true\n                             :avoids-assuming-conclusion? true\n                             :meaningful-without-prose? true\n                             :notes \"Explicitly states the exact extension/uniqueness claim for uniformly continuous maps on dense subsets of complete metric spaces.\"}}\n :alignments [{:formal-name \"extend_uniformContinuous_dense\"\n               :formal-statement \"∀ {X Y : Type*} [MetricSpace X] [CompleteSpace X] [MetricSpace Y] [CompleteSpace Y]\\n    {A : Set X} (hA : Dense A) {f : A → Y},\\n    UniformContinuous f → ∃! F : X → Y, Continuous F ∧ ∀ ⦃x⦄ (hx : x ∈ A), F x = f ⟨x, hx⟩\"\n               :informal-clause \"Proves the headline Stage 1 sentence asserting existence and uniqueness of the continuous extension.\"\n               :role :main-theorem}\n              {:formal-name \"dense_agree_implies_eq\"\n               :formal-statement \"∀ {X Y : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X] [T1Space Y] {A : Set X}\\n    (hA : Dense A) {g₁ g₂ : X → Y}, Continuous g₁ → Continuous g₂ → (∀ ⦃x⦄, x ∈ A → g₁ x = g₂ x) → g₁ = g₂\"\n               :informal-clause \"Used in Stage 1 to justify uniqueness: two continuous extensions agreeing on the dense set A must be identical.\"\n               :role :helper-lemma}]}\n```\n\n---\n\n**Why it’s hard.** The “extend from a dense subset” slogan is easy to misremember: you still have to show the image limits exist and are independent of the approximating sequence. That takes two ingredients students often forget to use together—uniform continuity (to convert Cauchy sequences in \\(A\\) into Cauchy sequences in \\(Y\\)) and completeness of \\(Y\\) (to produce the limit). Without that roadmap the proof devolves into case-by-case epsilons, and it becomes unclear where density is being used.\n\n**Key insight.** Fix \\(x\\in X\\). Pick any sequence \\((a_n)\\subseteq A\\) with \\(a_n\\to x\\). Uniform continuity turns \\((f(a_n))\\) into a Cauchy sequence, so it converges in the complete space \\(Y\\). Define \\(F(x)\\) to be this limit. Interleaving two approximating sequences shows the limit does not depend on the choice of \\((a_n)\\), so \\(F\\) is well defined and automatically satisfies \\(F|_A=f\\).\n\n**Complete proof.**  \n1. For each \\(x\\in X\\), choose \\((a_n)\\subseteq A\\) with \\(a_n\\to x\\) (density). Uniform continuity supplies \\(\\delta>0\\) for each \\(\\varepsilon>0\\); since \\((a_n)\\) is Cauchy, for large \\(m,n\\) we have \\(d_X(a_m,a_n)<\\delta\\), hence \\(d_Y(f(a_m),f(a_n))<\\varepsilon\\). Thus \\(f(a_n)\\) is Cauchy and converges in \\(Y\\). Set \\(F(x)=\\lim f(a_n)\\).  \n2. If \\((b_n)\\subseteq A\\) also converges to \\(x\\), interleave the two sequences to get \\(c_0=a_0,c_1=b_0,c_2=a_1,\\dots\\). The same uniform-continuity argument shows \\(f(c_n)\\) is Cauchy, so both subsequences \\((f(a_n))\\) and \\((f(b_n))\\) converge to the same limit; hence \\(F\\) is well defined and \\(F(x)=f(x)\\) for \\(x\\in A\\) (take \\(a_n=x\\)).  \n3. For continuity, let \\(x_k\\to x\\). Approximate each \\(x_k\\) by a sequence in \\(A\\), diagonalize, and reuse the Cauchy control to show \\(F(x_k)\\to F(x)\\); equivalently, given \\(\\varepsilon>0\\) pick the modulus \\(\\delta\\) from uniform continuity and note that if \\(d_X(x,y)<\\delta\\) then, by chasing their approximating sequences, \\(d_Y(F(x),F(y))<\\varepsilon\\).  \n4. For uniqueness, let \\(G:X\\to Y\\) be continuous with \\(G|_A=f\\). Given \\(x\\in X\\) and a sequence \\(a_n\\to x\\) with \\(a_n\\in A\\), continuity gives \\(G(x)=\\lim G(a_n)=\\lim f(a_n)=F(x)\\). Thus \\(G=F\\).\n\n(Only completeness of \\(Y\\) is really used; completeness of \\(X\\) is harmless but unnecessary.)\n\n**Lean 4 formalization.**  \nThe lemma\n```lean\ntheorem extend_uniformContinuous_dense\n  {A : Set X} (hA : Dense A) {f : A → Y}\n  (hf : UniformContinuous f) :\n  ∃! F : X → Y, Continuous F ∧ ∀ ⦃x⦄ (hx : x ∈ A), F x = f ⟨x, hx⟩\n```\nlives in `/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/M99A04/Apm_v2_m99A04_1775007855572/Main.lean`.  It’s a straightforward wrapper around mathlib’s `Dense.extend` API: `hA.uniformContinuous_extend hf` supplies the uniformly continuous extension, `hA.extend_of_ind hf` proves agreement on \\(A\\), and `hA.extend_unique` gives uniqueness.  `lake build` succeeds; the only warnings are pre-existing (unused variables in `ApmCanaries/C2Analysis.lean` and unused section variables in `ApmCanaries/C4Functional.lean`), so no new issues were introduced.\n\n**What connects.** This “dense uniform extension” story is ubiquitous. It underlies completion theory (extending maps from a dense subspace to a Banach space), construction of orthogonal projections, and the functional-analytic trick of defining operators first on a dense core (e.g. Schwartz functions) before closing them. Whenever you can approximate points in \\(X\\) by elements of a dense set while controlling images with a uniform modulus, this blueprint gives you a canonical extension and shows it is unique.", :frame-workspace {:frame/lean-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/M99A04/Apm_v2_m99A04_1775007855572", :frame/id "apm-v2-m99A04-1775007855572", :workspace/owner-repo "futon6", :workspace/generated-at "2026-04-01T01:44:15.593677Z", :frame/shared-extension-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Local", :frame/module-root "ApmCanaries.Frames.M99A04.Apm_v2_m99A04_1775007855572", :proof/problem-id "m99A04", :workspace/schema "proof-frame-workspace.v1", :frame/workspace-root "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/m99A04/apm-v2-m99A04-1775007855572", :artifacts {:proof-plan "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/m99A04/apm-v2-m99A04-1775007855572/proof-plan.edn", :formal-alignment "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/m99A04/apm-v2-m99A04-1775007855572/formal-alignment.edn", :changelog "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/m99A04/apm-v2-m99A04-1775007855572/changelog.edn", :execute-notes "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/m99A04/apm-v2-m99A04-1775007855572/execute.md", :workspace-readme "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/m99A04/apm-v2-m99A04-1775007855572/README.md", :workspace-metadata "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/m99A04/apm-v2-m99A04-1775007855572/workspace.json", :lean-main "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/M99A04/Apm_v2_m99A04_1775007855572/Main.lean", :lean-scratch "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/M99A04/Apm_v2_m99A04_1775007855572/Scratch.lean"}}, :artifacts ["/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/M99A04/Apm_v2_m99A04_1775007855572/Main.lean" "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/M99A04/Apm_v2_m9